  "response": "The **Pushpak Vimana** is a mythical flying chariot described in ancient Indian texts, particularly the *Ramayana*, where it is associated with the god Kubera and later with the demon king Ravana. There is no credible historical or archaeological evidence to suggest that the Pushpak Vimana has been found in Afghanistan or anywhere else, as it is considered a legendary or allegorical construct rather than a physical artifact.\n\nHowever, in recent years, there have been speculative claims and theories, often circulated in fringe circles or sensational media, suggesting that ancient aircraft or vimana-like structures have been discovered in Afghanistan or other parts of the world. These claims are typically not supported by mainstream archaeology or science and are often tied to pseudoscientific or mythological narratives.\n\nFor example, some theories point to ancient advanced technologies or extraterrestrial connections based on interpretations of vague or misinterpreted archaeological findings. In Afghanistan, where there is a rich history of ancient civilizations like the Bactrians and the influence of Indian and Persian cultures, such claims occasionally arise but remain unsubstantiated.\n\nIn summary, while the Pushpak Vimana is a fascinating part of Indian mythology, there is no verified evidence of its existence or discovery in Afghanistan or elsewhere. Any claims of its discovery should be approached with skepticism and critically evaluated.",
